[<p class="sh2"><span>SIGN UP</span> FOR OUR NEWSLETTER</p>, <p>The set of 176 icons that were originally created for Japan\u2019s NTT DOCOMO are\xa0the first known set of emojis to be created back in 1999, leading the pictograph-based texting language into the modern world.</p>, <p class="sh2"><span>SIGN UP</span> FOR OUR NEWSLETTER</p>, <p>\u201cWe are thrilled to announce the addition of NTT DOCOMO\u2019s original set of 176 emoji to the MoMA collection,\u201d <a href="/web/20161028151406/https://medium.com/moma/the-original-emoji-set-has-been-added-to-the-museum-of-modern-arts-collection-c6060e141f61#.1i0vc5r79">announced MoMA on their blog Wednesday</a>.\xa0\u201cDeveloped under the supervision of Shigetaka Kurita and released for cell phones in 1999, these 12 x 12 pixel humble masterpieces of design planted the seeds for the explosive growth of a new visual language.\u201d</p>, <p>\u201cToday\u2019s emoji (the current Unicode set numbers nearly 1,800) have evolved far beyond Kurita\u2019s original 176 designs for NTT DOCOMO,\u201d they continued. \u201cHowever, the DNA for today\u2019s set is clearly present in Kurita\u2019s humble, pixelated, seminal emoji.\u201d</p>, <p>In their announcement, MoMA also hint at a\xa0\u201cforthcoming installation\u2026 opening in early December\u201d that \u201cwill further elaborate on the evolution of emoji and give visitors an opportunity to see them in a new light (and no doubt inspire a few selfies).\u201d</p>, <p>In 2012, MoMA <a href="/web/20161028151406/https://www.wired.com/2012/11/moma-videogames/">announced the acquisition of 14 videogames to be exhibited at the museum</a> alongside its collection of world-renowned paintings by Salvador Dali, Vincent van Gogh, Pablo Picasso, and Andy Warhol.</p>, <p>The museum <a href="/web/20161028151406/http://www.develop-online.net/news/minecraft-and-classic-games-join-moma-exhibit/0115277">has since added even more titles</a>, and their collection currently includes such games as <em>Minecraft</em>, <em>Myst</em>, <em>Dwarf Fortress</em>, <em>Portal</em>, <em>Pac-Man</em>, <em>The Sims</em>, and <em>Pong</em>.</p>, <p>Games <a href="/web/20161028151406/https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_video_games_in_the_Museum_of_Modern_Art">on the museum\u2019s wishlist</a> include <em>Donkey Kong</em>, <em>Super Mario Bros.</em>, <em>The Legend of Zelda</em>, and <em>Grim Fandango</em>.</p>, <p><em><i>Charlie Nash is a reporter\xa0for\xa0Breitbart Tech. You can follow him\xa0on Twitter\xa0</i><span class="s2"><i><a class=" x5l x5l x5l x5l" href="/web/20161028151406/https://twitter.com/mrnashington" rel="noopener" target="_blank">@MrNashington</a>\xa0or\xa0<a class=" x5l x5l x5l x5l" href="/web/20161028151406/https://www.facebook.com/CharlieWNash" rel="noopener" target="_blank">like his page at Facebook</a>.</i></span></em></p>]